ire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1245–24 June 1314":"1245–24 June 1314","1245–1314":"1245–1314","1220–Female":"1220–Deceased","1270–1314":"1270–1314","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Deceased","24 June 1314":"24 June 1314","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","Aft 1298":"after 1298","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","Abt 1270":"about 1270","Abt 24 June 1314":"about 24 June 1314","1270":"1270","Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Barclay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name of English origin, from any of several places so called, such as Berkley in Somerset or Berkeley in Gloucestershire, both named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: The surname was brought to Scotland from southwestern England in the 12th century; Walter de Berchelai or Berkelai was Chamberlain of Scotland in 1165. It was long assumed that they were from the family that held Berkeley Castle in Gloucestershire, but the historian G. W. S. Barrow (1973, <i>The Kingdom of the Scots</i>) adduced evidence that they are more probably from Berkley in Somerset."],"variants":[{"name":"Barkley","meanings":["English and northern Irish (Antrim): variant of   Barclay  .","Americanized form of German   Berkel   or of some other similar (like-sounding) German surname."]},{"name":"Barclift","meanings":["Perhaps an altered form of Scottish   Barclay  ."]},{"name":"Berkeley","meanings":["English: habitational name from one or more of the numerous places so named, such as Berkeley in Gloucestershire, named in Old English with <i>be(o)rc</i> ‘birch’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare Scottish   Barclay  .","Jewish (American): adoption of the English surname (see 1 above) in place of   Berkowitz  ."]},{"name":"Brickley","meanings":["English and Irish: metathesized form of   Barclay  ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Barclay was born in 1245, in Scotland, his father, Hugh de Berkeley 6th Laird of Towie, was 20 and his mother, Lady Hugh de Berkeley Laird of Towie, was 16. He had at least 1 son with Lady David Barclay Sr.. He died on 24 June 1314, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1245–24 June 1314":"1245–24. juuni 1314","1245–1314":"1245–1314","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1270–1314":"1270–1314","1225–1298":"1225–1298","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","24 June 1314":"24. juuni 1314","1314":"1314","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","Aft 1298":"pärast 1298","1298":"1298","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","Abt 1270":"umbes 1270","Abt 24 June 1314":"umbes 24. juuni 1314","1270":"1270","Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Scotland":"Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland","Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland":"Cullen, Banffshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1245–24 June 1314":"1245–24. ke